    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Pieter Nanninck to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 5 October 1537)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>Although Ludolphus, who has arrived with Rutger Pathius, has not brought
                            any letter, he has reported that Oláh is well. Nanninck is suffering
                            from his eye disease, he inherited trouble from two poets: Virgil had
                            headaches, while Horace had eye infections. He has taken on Pathius’
                            brother as a convivial fellow, but in a way that Nanninck’s brother is
                            feeding him and Nanninck is teaching him, this way they divide worry and
                            profit between them. Both Oláh and the Queen trust Pathius so much that
                            they do not need to worry they will be disappointed; but he does not
                            want Pathius to learn that Nanninck’s brother had his doubts. He cannot
                            write more now due to his grief, he has lost his sister.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Idem Nicolao Olao salutem plurimam. </p>
                <p>Etsi nihil litterarum ad me attulit <persName>Ludolphus</persName><note
                        type="critic">He was probably a protégé of Oláh, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Polet</hi> 1936, 259.</note> noster, qui huc cum
                        <persName>fratre</persName><note type="critic">See Ep. 590. Cap.
                        2.</note><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15370928_1</ref>
                    <persName>Rutgeri</persName><note type="critic">Rutger Pathius.</note> venit,
                    tamen quia mihi <milestone unit="pb"/>te recte valere nuntiavit, multisque negotiis impeditum esse, cur minus
                    scriberes, statui mollius mihi ferendum esse desiderium tuarum litterarum, quod
                    tum lenies, ubi tua negotia permiserint. Nos cum medicis diu luctati sumus
                    adversus lippitudinem,<note type="critic">See Ep.
                        583.</note><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15370310_1</ref> quam tamen in hoc genere mali
                    rectius ὀφθαλμίαν<note type="critic">‘eye disease’.</note> vocavero. Duo summi
                    poetae sua vitia in me exonerarunt: <persName>Vergilius</persName> capitis
                    dolorem, <persName>Horatius</persName> lippitudinem, mallem potius virtutes
                    transtulissent ἀλλὰ τὰ παρόντα <choice>
                        <orig>ἐὐ</orig>
                        <supplied>εὖ</supplied>
                    </choice> τίθεσθαι δεῖ.<note type="critic">‘but the current things have to be
                        settled’.</note> Ego <persName>fratrem</persName>
                    <persName>Rutgeri</persName> tui in ὁμοτράπεζον<note type="critic">‘convivial
                        fellow’.</note> accepi, quamquam alendi negotium in <persName>fratrem
                        meum</persName><note type="critic">We do not know his name, but according to
                        Nanninck, he later entered the service of Emperor Charles V and settled in
                        Ghent. Nanninck reports in 1548 that his brother had been the victim of a
                        night attack at the Imperial Court and killed one of his assailants but he
                        was released thanks to the intercession of his powerful friends and the
                        Hague Senate, see <hi rend="smallcap">Polet</hi> 1936, 3.</note> transtuli,
                    docendi mihi reservavi, ita inter nos cura et lucrum partitur; is, ut est
                    sollicitus, praesertim in nova familia rogavit ex me, numquid periculi in
                    posterum foret de solutione; respondi omnia secura esse. Talem esse
                        <persName>Rutgerum</persName>, et in tanta gratia apud reginam, ut nihil
                    tale de eo metuendum sit, deinde tui apud eum tanta reverentia, ut etiam si
                    talis non esset, qualis quam maxime est, te tamen salvo, nunquam illum ausurum
                    solutionem differre, tantum abesse, ut omitteret, deinde ipsum iuvenem verbis
                    tuis mihi commendatum, idque me scire ex litteris
                        <persName>Dani</persName>,<note type="critic">Jakob Jespersen.</note> si
                    modo ea scripsit ex tuo mandato. Nolim tamen has fratris mei haesitationes
                        <persName>Rutgero</persName> indices, scio enim eum stulta sollicitudine
                    moveri, teque mihi ultro indicaturum, si quid in hoc nomine periculi esset, quod
                    ego nullum omnino arbitror. </p>
                <p>Nos maluimus pauca, quam nihil scribere, ne aut opportunitate <milestone unit="pb"/>tabellarii non uterer, aut loquacitate tuas hoc tempore gravissimas
                    occupationes accumularem, deinde luctus, in quo nunc sum, amisi enim unicam
                        <persName>sororem</persName>,<note type="critic">Marguerite, wife of Jordan
                        van Foreest, died in September 1537, see <hi rend="smallcap">Polet</hi>
                        1936, 3.</note> vix mihi permittit ullum usum litterarum, cuius causa brevi
                    in <placeName>Hollandiam</placeName> propero. Tu, mi Unice et Doctissime et
                    Humanissime Patrone, diu nobis studiisque feliciter vivas. </p>
                <p>3. Nonas Octobres 1537.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
